# Rust Doesn't Have a Garbage Collector

This is a common misconception worth clarifying directly. **Rust has no garbage collector** — this is actually one of its defining features and primary design goals.

---

## How Rust Manages Memory Instead

Rust uses a compile-time system called **Ownership** with three core rules:

### 1. Ownership Rules
```rust
// Each value has exactly one owner
let s1 = String::from("hello");  // s1 owns the string

let s2 = s1;                     // ownership MOVES to s2
// println!("{}", s1);           // COMPILE ERROR - s1 is no longer valid

// Memory is freed automatically when owner goes out of scope
```

### 2. Borrowing & References
```rust
fn calculate_length(s: &String) -> usize {  // borrow, don't take ownership
    s.len()
}  // s goes out of scope but doesn't free memory (it doesn't own it)

let s1 = String::from("hello");
let len = calculate_length(&s1);
println!("{} has length {}", s1, len);  // s1 still valid
```

### 3. Lifetimes
```rust
// Compiler tracks how long references are valid
fn longest<'a>(x: &'a str, y: &'a str) -> &'a str {
    if x.len() > y.len() { x } else { y }
}
// 'a tells compiler the returned reference lives as long as
// the shorter of x and y
```

### 4. The Drop Trait (Destructors)
```rust
struct MyResource {
    data: String,
}

impl Drop for MyResource {
    fn drop(&mut self) {
        println!("Freeing resource: {}", self.data);
        // cleanup happens automatically here
    }
}

{
    let r = MyResource { data: String::from("important") };
    // use r...
}  // drop() called HERE automatically - deterministic!
```

